			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Swarm Kiting Question<a name="51890"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 14 04 1:54 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Woot! I'm <i>interesting</i>! ;)
<br />

<br />
Well I read pretty much every kiting guide on this website and got a general idea of what to do. So last night I set out to practice my new found swarm-kiting techniques.
<br />

<br />
The guides that I found the most helpful were <a href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=58&amp;ForumID=132">Shassiash's Guide</a> as well as <a href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=51&amp;ForumID=132">Cevinzol's Guide</a>. However, neither guide answered my question about why a single mob would stray and continue to chase me while my pet was engaged in the pack fight.
<br />

<br />
What I learned is that after you break your pet and chant him down, you MUST switch to the mob that your pet was beating on and make him your next pet. He will go quicker since he's been beaten by your former pet, so be ready.  If you don't get the mob your pet has beaten on, he will chase you down, presumably because the agro from the former pet is now on you, and doesn't transfer to your new pet.
<br />

<br />
A few things from the aforementioned guides that I found most helpful:
<br />

<br />
Shassiash is very correct in stating that speed is everything. Letting Selo’s fade killed me.
<br />

<br />
Shassiah also mentioned snaring the last mob, whereas Cevinzol didn’t have the snare song up. I found this to be very important!! Another bard was kiting (I was watching) and he let his last mob wander out a little far. The wanderer sent back a spider, which the bard began to kite. A few minutes later a few more spiders, and some treeants. Eventually the wanderer came back with a few other mobs, and it got out of control. That one mob who was at 6% ended up training half the zone. 
<br />

<br />
Use the hotkey for pet attack/pet target. It’s 2 lines: /pet attack (on line 1) /pet target (on line 2) Then when you send your pet in to attack, it will target him back. You can stand there and watch him until his health is in the 20% range (I usually wait until 15%) then break the charm and he’s all ready for your chant down. Toggle to the mob with less health than the others, and charm him for your next go round.
<br />

<br />
Don’t turn back into the pack. Every now and again I would cut my circle short and get hit. One or two mistakes like that and you’re dead.
<br />

<br />
F9 is the default key for changing your camera angle (not F8 as in Cevinzol’s guide). It takes some getting used to... I haven’t decided if I’ll switch or not.
<br />

<br />
An open UI is important for allowing you to see as much of the screen as possible. I use <a href="http://www.theorder.net/message_board/viewthread.php?action=attachment&amp;tid=4414&amp;pid=28158">SOES</a>, however I heard that it’s not supported anymore.<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-6.gif" border="0" alt="Sad" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
Anyway, this is the most fun I've had in the game! It's also the most never-wracking when I started out. 
<br />

<br />
Now a question! Will looting break your charm?</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
