				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Swarm Kiting Question<a name="51925"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 14 04 3:55 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">What I learned is that after you break your pet and chant him down, you MUST switch to the mob that your pet was beating on and make him your next pet.</span></blockquote>Not true.  I never bother figuring out which mob I am going to kill next, I just target the first one I can.
<br />

<br />
A note: I don't know if I put in the guide but...When I am chanting down my now ex pet I drag them far away from where I am going to be charming and gathering his old friends to him.  While they are back on the new pet I run to the corpse and loot it.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Shassiah also mentioned snaring the last mob, whereas Cevinzol didn’t have the snare song up. I found this to be very important!! Another bard was kiting (I was watching) and he let his last mob wander out a little far. The wanderer sent back a spider, which the bard began to kite. A few minutes later a few more spiders, and some treeants. Eventually the wanderer came back with a few other mobs, and it got out of control. That one mob who was at 6% ended up training half the zone</span></blockquote>This is exactly why I noted that you needed to snare that last one.  I ended up having to kill nearly 10 extra unwanted mobs one time and the rest of PoN kept coming... had to zone.  I learned my lesson and put it in my guide.
<br />

<br />
Back to the issue of mobs not sticking to your pet.  Part of it is probably proximity.   What I do when swarming is make a pet, after I've got the entire swarm following me and grouped nicely, and then park him in a spot where I can move away from them all.  Then, I run them away and then back towards him, I make sure that I run directly over my pet with them far behind and them in a straight line between us (me and pet) at which point I send pet in to attack one of the pack.  This usually manages to get all of them on him.  It is rare for any to keep coming after me if the distance is good enough.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
