			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Swarm Kiting Question<a name="52158"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 15 04 3:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The strays were the biggest problem for me when I was first learning how to swarm, I was a little intimidated by the whole thing and when I told the pet to attack and saw half the mobs peel away to come after me, I freaked out. I had another bard friend explain to me that it has to do with social aggro radius, and the fact that they are moving the whole time, even if it appears they are right next to each other, the server ticks can make the short range of social aggro miss one or two of them. This seems to always happen and be a pretty common occurance during swarming, just take it into consideration and don't panic, the good lady Shass already explained the best way to deal with it, drag them back <u>through</u> your pet and they should aggro immediately when they get there, whatever you do <u>don't</u> cast anything on them, like Shass said it's all about aggro and when you start the swarm you have barely any. I did notice some mobs were more succeptible to this wandering, most likely because thier aggro ranges are bigger/smaller, always try to kite similar mobs or the same type of mobs, it can only help. As for Selo's running out, I had that problem as well and I solved it by using SoW potions, I always give that tip to new bards trying to swarm, eliminating another distraction like worrying about Selo's really helps when you are learning the ropes. One more tip, and this is personal preference but I like it, set up your toggle last target button (I set mine to W) it really helps. Target the starting mob, chant or proxy aggro, then run around and get your swarm, then hit F8 to target the closest one in the pack, hit your pet attack key then hit toggle last target (W) now you're back on your pet, watch it's health, break the charm then chant it down, then hit W again and you're targetted on your pet's last opponent, it makes it easier IMO but I know a lot of folks here probably just watch the pet window and keep the pet's last target locked in anyways. 
<br />
So I hope that helps and Merry Swarming to you, it's a h*ll of a lot of fun and one of my favorite things to do in EQ, have a blast dude!
<br />
 <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /></span></td>
