			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Swarm Kiting Question<a name="52705"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 19 04 7:16 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Actually, you'll get swarm parts not on the charmed pet for a couple of reasons...
<br />

<br />
1) Swarm size... 1 Charmed Pet will &quot;tank&quot; up to 4 mobs without an issue.  If you have more than 4 mobs, your pet will only snag one when told to attack.  The others in the swarm will run toward you instead.  Kite a loop and stop with your pet between you and the rest of the swarm.  The swarm should stop chasing you and gang up on the pet again.
<br />

<br />
2) The Shield Ability... warrior type mobs (Ravenous Nightstalker Camp) get the ability to shield their friends.  Watch closely and you will see this often.  Basically what they do is soak up some of the damage you are putting out on your target mob.  So, say you charm one, it gets to 20%, you break charm and toss the DOTs... good plan, but if one of the other mobs starts shielding your target, that mob will take part of the damage your DOTs are applying.  Over time, that damage adds up and can cause a shielding mob to ignore your pets all together and single you out alone.  If your mana regen is max'd, just Fade out of these situations.  If not, Song of Dawn is your friend.  I few bursts of Dawn and the damage aggro you have earned will be gone, the mob will once more be interested in your pet.  (Flies and Rats in PoDisease are also bad about shielding each other)
<br />

<br />
3) Lost charmed mobs... happens to most bards eventually.  You charm mob 1, it breaks charm while you are busy doing &lt;whatever&gt;, and you charm mob 2.  Charm is huge aggro.  Most mobs once charmed will continue to pursue you regardless of what you lay on them.  Again, Fade or Song of Dawn is your friend.  With practice you'll get this reason less and less.  If you're going to stop to say loot a kill while your pet is fighting, check your pet's hp % as you loot.  If charm breaks while you are looting, you're gonna stand up from looting with no target, but at least you might be able to pick the same mob outta the swarm since you have some idea where his hp % should be.  IMO that's the most common time you lose a pet in the swarm.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
